# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-english
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] The **2021 Australian census**, simply called the **2021 Census**, was the eighteenth national Census of Population and Housing in Australia.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] The 2021 Census took place on 10 August 2021, and was conducted by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] It had a response rate of 96.1%, up from the 95.1% at the 2016 census.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] The total population of the Commonwealth of Australia was counted as 25,422,788, an increase of 8.6 per cent or 2,020,896 people over the previous 2016 census.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Results from the 2021 census were released to the public on 28 June 2022 from the Australian Bureau of Statistics website.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] A small amount of additional 2021 census data was released in October 2022 and in 2023.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Australia's next census is scheduled to take place in 2026.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] The census was undertaken during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] It therefore provided a clear snapshot of how the pandemic impacted Australian society.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] In Australia, completing the census is compulsory for all people in Australia on census night, only excluding foreign diplomats and their families.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Census data is used to "help governments, businesses, not-for-profit and community organisations across the country make informed decisions", including helping governments to plan the provision of services.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] An independent report from Lateral Economics found that for every $1 of investment on the census, $6 of benefits are created in the Australian economy.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Since the 2001 Census, all households have the option of allowing their census data, including personal information such as names and addresses, to be stored by the National Archives of Australia (NAA) for 99 years.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] 99 years after Census Night, the NAA will release that data to the public in a Census Time Capsule.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Censuses stored by the NAA cannot by accessed, amended, or retrieved by anyone, including courts and tribunal, until their release, the first of which will occur in 2100.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] The 2020 Census Test occurred on 27 October 2020 with around 100,000 households from Sydney, Adelaide, Darwin, and Canberra, as well as communities in Karratha, Warrnambool, and Alice Springs Town Camps.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Every census, the ABS makes a recommendation to the Australian Government on the topics to be included, based on the benefit that data would provide to Australia.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Through the *Census and Statistics Amendment (Statistical Information) Regulations 2020*, the federal parliament approves topics that may be included.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] For the 2021 census, the ABS had been authorised to include questions relating to long-term health conditions and service in the Australian Defence Force, and would not continue asking questions about home internet access considering the rise of mobile devices.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] This represented the first significant change to census topics since 2006.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Through late 2017, the ABS began discussions with major census data users on what was needed.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] From 3 April to 30 June 2018, a formal consultation process occurred on the online "ABS Consultation Hub", with the ABS receiving 450 submissions, 315 of which were published with consent.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Since 2006, the ABS has allowed the census to be completed online, moving in 2016 to be digital-first.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Like 2016, the 2021 Census was primarily collected online, with paper census forms being available on request for any household.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] In 2016, around a third of all households requested and completed their census using the paper form.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] The population counts for Australian states and territories were that New South Wales remains the most populous state, with 8,072,163 people counted, ahead of Victoria (6,503,491) and Queensland (5,156,138).
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Of all residents over two-thirds (72.4% or 18,235,690) were born in Australia.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] Over a quarter of the population (27.6% or 7,502,450 persons) said they were born overseas.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] After Australia, England is the most common birthplace with 927,490 people.
[src:australian-english/2021-australian-census] India became the third-largest country of birth, surpassing China and New Zealand.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] A second edition of *A Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles* (DCHP-2), was then created by expanding and partially revising the first edition's data set.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] DCHP-2 was published in 2017 as an academic project by the University of British Columbia, and is only available as a free-access online dictionary.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] A third edition (DCHP-3), this time in mobile-friendly format, was released in 2025 with 181 new meanings relating to minoritized groups and the originally more informal vocabulary.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The origins of the first Canadian Dictionary (DCHP-1) can be linked to American Lexicographer Charles Julien Lovell just after WW2 in 1946.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Predating this, the American OED dictionary included the small number of Canadian words found in their research as was the practice during this time for larger varieties.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Lovell, working at the time for the University of Chicago and the Dictionary of Americanisms, felt that there was a true distinction between American words and Canadian ones.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] This led Lovell to create a separate file for words that he deemed to be Canadian as he traversed across the country.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] In 1954, after creation of the Canadian Linguistic Association, Lovell proposed his idea of the creation of the first Canadian Dictionary, and shortly after submitted an article on the “Lexicographical Challenges of Canadian English”.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] In March 1960, funding was granted to create the first Canadian Dictionary, DCHP-1 (Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles).Charles Lovell died just weeks later.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The lead of the project would then be taken on and headed by Lovell's colleague and friend, Walter Spencer Avis.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] A professor of English at the Royal Military College in Kingston, Ontario.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Without intention, Avis, came to become a dictionary editor and leader to complete DCHP-1.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Along with him, Patrick Drysdale, Chuck Crate, Douglas Leechman, and Mathew Scargill (these names, with Avis and Lovell would become known as the big six of creating Canadian English).
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Drysdale focused on working with the publisher of the dictionary in Toronto, W.J.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Gage publishing and relayed information to the team.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Avis, Crate, And Leechman were responsible for controlling the majority of the information brought in through slips.> Scargill, the “director of the Lexicographical Centre in Victoria'' was the promoter and organizer of the DCHP.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The Publisher, Gage, requested that four versions of the dictionary were to be made: the Beginning Dictionary, Intermediate Dictionary, Senior Dictionary, and the Complete version DCHP-1.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The final dictionary was completed just in time for Canadians' Centennial year In November 1967.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] In 2006, after almost 40 years of existence without any updates, work on a new edition was started.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Nelson Education Ltd., which had acquired Gage Ltd. and with it the rights to the DCHP-1 had been actively seeking collaborators in academia to produce a new edition of the DCHP-1.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] This project, DCHP-2, was proposed at a conference on Canadian English in January 2005, and formally commenced at the University of British Columbia's Department of English in August 2006, after a year of preparatory work.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Since 2009, DCHP-2 has had no association with Nelson Ltd. or any other publisher and had been a purely academic project.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Completed in 2011 after automatic scanning and manual proofreading by a team at UBC, *DCHP*-1 was republished in open access as of 2013, thanks to Nelson Ltd.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] 2013), and is available as a free website, *DCHP*-1 Online.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The second edition was edited by Stefan Dollinger (editor-in-chief) and Margery Fee (associate editor) and includes features not part of the first edition: a six-way classification system for Canadianisms, the Dictionary Editing Tool, and the Bank of Canadian English (BCE), a quotation database.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The process of digitization started with the scanning and of the first edition of the dictionary (DCHP-1).
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The online version of DCHP-1 was made publicly accessible in 2013.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The main data collection phase for the DCHP-2 lasted from 2007 to 2010 and included 36,000 new citations derived from the 7,000 new potential headwords found in The Canadian Oxford Dictionary and other sources.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Potential headwords and citations were cross-checked with other varieties of English using web data and entered into the Bank of Canadian English, a quotation filing system, to be proofread and edited.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The potential headwords and citations were then classified into one of the six categories of Canadianisms according to their distinctive histories in Canada, cultural significance, or usage frequency.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] DCHP-2 was released online on 17 March 2017.{{source needed}} The launch coincided with the 57th anniversary of Charles J.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Lovell's passing, the founding editor of DCHP-1.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] DCHP-1 was launched as a Centennial project; DCHP-2 was launched as a Sesquicentennial contribution with the goal of lifting the discussion about Canadianisms, and about Canadian English more generally, on an empirically sounder footing.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The Third Edition was released on 15 May 2025.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Its code base was rewritten to accommodate mobile phone use and includes an editorial update of 181 meanings for a total of 12,000 headwords and 14,500 meanings from 1500 to 2025.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Work began in 2022 and lasted through May 2025.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The third edition update focuses on underrepresented groups, e.g.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] First Nations (lahal, kokum, skoden), and vocabulary from informal origins, e.g. urban slang (freezie, ding, levidrome) and rural slang (klick, hang a larry, shit-kicking).
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The *Toronto Star* referred to it as a great "birthday gift for the nation" of Canada, *The Globe and Mail* lauded its detail (e.g. the entry on *eh*, which is almost 5000 words long) and the CBC The National Newscast featured DCHP-2 in April 2017 as the topic of its cultural news item of the day.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] There was dissatisfaction with the dictionaries of the period, so in June 1746 a group of London booksellers contracted Johnson to write a dictionary for the sum of 1,500 guineas (£1,575), equivalent to about £300,000 in 2025.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson took seven years to complete the work, although he had claimed he could finish it in three.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] He did so single-handedly, with only clerical assistance to copy the illustrative quotations that he had marked in books.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson produced several revised editions during his life.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Until the completion of the *Oxford English Dictionary* 173 years later, Johnson's was viewed as the pre-eminent English dictionary.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] According to Walter Jackson Bate, the Dictionary "easily ranks as one of the greatest single achievements of scholarship, and probably the greatest ever performed by one individual who laboured under anything like the disadvantages in a comparable length of time".
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In earlier times, books had been regarded with something approaching veneration, but by the mid-eighteenth century this was no longer the case.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The rise of literacy among the general public, combined with the technical advances in the mechanics of printing and bookbinding, meant that for the first time, books, texts, maps, pamphlets and newspapers were widely available to the general public at a reasonable cost.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Such an explosion of the printed word demanded a set pattern of grammar, definition, and spelling for those words.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This could be achieved by means of an authoritative dictionary of the English language.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 1746, a consortium of London's most successful printers, including Robert Dodsley and Thomas Longman – none could afford to undertake it alone – set out to satisfy and capitalise on this need by the ever-increasing reading and writing public.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was not the first English dictionary, nor even among the first dozen.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Over the previous 150 years more than twenty dictionaries had been published in England, the oldest of these being a Latin-English "wordbook" by Sir Thomas Elyot published in 1538.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The next to appear was by Richard Mulcaster, a headmaster, in 1583.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It was the first English dictionary to use quotations ("illustrations") to give meaning to the word; in none of these dictionaries so far were there any actual definitions of words.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This was to change, to a small extent, in schoolmaster Robert Cawdrey's *Table Alphabeticall*, published in 1604.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Though it contained only 2,449 words, and no word beginning with the letters *W*, *X*, or *Y*, this was the first monolingual English dictionary.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Several more dictionaries followed: in Latin, English, French and Italian.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Benjamin Martin's *Lingua Britannica Reformata* (1749) and Ainsworth's *Thesaurus Linguae Latinae* (1737) are both significant, in that they define entries in separate senses, or aspects, of the word.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The problem with these dictionaries was that they tended to be little more than poorly organised and poorly researched glossaries of "hard words": words that were technical, foreign, obscure or antiquated.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Perhaps the greatest single fault of these early lexicographers was, as historian Henry Hitchings put it, that they "failed to give sufficient sense of [the English] language as it appeared *in use*." In that sense Dr.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was the first to comprehensively document the English lexicon.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was prepared at 17 Gough Square, London, an eclectic household, between the years of 1746 and 1755.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] By 1747 Johnson had written his *Plan of a Dictionary of the English Language*, which spelled out his intentions and proposed methodology for preparing his document.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's *Plan* received the patronage of Philip Stanhope, 4th Earl of Chesterfield but not to Johnson's pleasure.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Chesterfield did not care about praise, but was instead interested by Johnson's abilities.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Seven years after first meeting Johnson to discuss the work, Chesterfield wrote two anonymous essays in *The World* that recommended the *Dictionary*.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] However, Johnson did not appreciate the tone of the essay, and he felt that Chesterfield had not made good on his promise to be the work's patron.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The words "Samuel Johnson" and "English Language" were printed in red; the rest was printed in black.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The preface and headings were set in 4.6 mm "English" type, the text—double columned—was set in a typeface like Caslon.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This first edition of the dictionary contained a 42,773-word list, to which only a few more were added in subsequent editions.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] One of Johnson's important innovations was to illustrate the meanings of his words by literary quotation, of which there are around 114,000, from around 500 authors.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The authors most frequently cited by Johnson include Shakespeare, Milton and Dryden.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Furthermore, Johnson, unlike Bailey, added notes on a word's usage, rather than being merely descriptive.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Unlike most modern lexicographers, Johnson introduced humour or prejudice into quite a number of his definitions.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] On a more serious level, Johnson's work showed a heretofore unseen meticulousness.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The original goal was to publish the dictionary in two folio volumes, A–K and L–Z, but that soon proved unwieldy, unprofitable, and unrealistic.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Subsequent printings ran to four volumes; even these formed a stack 10 inches (25 cm) tall, and weighed in at nearly 21 pounds (9.5 kg).
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In addition to the sheer physical heft of Johnson's dictionary, came the equally hefty price: £4/10/– (equivalent to approximately £880 in 2025).
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] So discouraging was the price that by 1784, thirty years after the first edition was published, when the dictionary had by then run through five editions, only about 6,000 copies were in circulation—an average sale of 200 books a year for thirty years.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's etymologies would be considered poor by modern standards, and he gave little guide to pronunciation; one example being "Cough: A convulsion of the lungs, vellicated by some sharp serosity.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Much of his dictionary was prescriptivist.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It was also linguistically conservative, advocating traditional spellings such as *publick* rather than the simpler spellings that would be favoured 73 years later by Noah Webster.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The dictionary is in alphabetical order according to the eighteenth-century English alphabet.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In the eighteenth century, the letters I and J were considered different forms of the same letter; the same with letters U and V.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] As a result, in Johnson's dictionary the word jargon comes before the word idle, and vagabond comes before ultimate.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In spite of its shortcomings, the dictionary was far and away the best of its day.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Its scope and structure were carried forward in dictionaries that followed, including Noah Webster's *Webster's Dictionary* in 1828 and the *Oxford English Dictionary* later in the same century.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Immediately after publication "The *Dictionary* was enthusiastically written up in important periodicals such as the *London Magazine* and—none too surprisingly—the *Gentleman's Magazine*.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In the latter it received an eight-page notice".
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Furthermore, Johnson's approach was not 'sufficiently grammatical'".
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] He gave up the house in Gough Square in March 1759, probably for lack of funds.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Yet, just as Johnson was plunging into another trough of despondency, the reputation of the *Dictionary* at last brought reward.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In July 1762 Johnson was granted a state pension of £300 a year by the twenty-four-year-old monarch, George III.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] As lexicography developed, faults were found with Johnson's work: "From an early stage there were noisy detractors.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Perhaps the loudest of them was John Horne Tooke ...
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was made when etymology was largely based on guesswork.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] His Classical leanings led him to prefer spellings that pointed to Latin or Greek sources, "while his lack of sound scholarship prevented him from detecting their frequent errors".
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] For example, he preferred the spelling *ache* over *ake* as he wrongly thought it came from the Greek *achos*.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Some of his spelling choices were also inconsistent: "while retaining the Latin *p* in *receipt* he left it out of *deceit*; he spelled *deign* one way and *disdain* another; he spelled *uphill* but *downhil*, *muckhill* but *dunghil*, *instill* but *distil*, *inthrall* but *disenthral*".
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's general rule, therefore, can only take place where custom has not plainly decided.' Nevertheless, Walker scrupulously followed Johnson's explanations of words, as did many contemporary dictionaries.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Despite the criticisms, "The influence of the *Dictionary* was sweeping.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson established both a methodology for how dictionaries should be put together and a paradigm for how entries should be presented.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Anyone who sought to create a dictionary, post-Johnson, did so in his shadow." "In his history of the *Oxford English Dictionary*, Simon Winchester asserts of its eighteenth-century predecessor that 'by the end of the century every educated household had, or had access to, the great book.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 2005, the Royal Mint issued a commemorative fifty pence coin celebrating the 250th anniversary of the dictionary's publication.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's influence was not confined to Britain and English: "The president of the Florentine Accademia declared that the *Dictionary* would be 'a perpetual Monument of Fame to the Author, an Honour to his own Country in particular, and a general Benefit to the Republic of Letters'.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's work served as a model for lexicographers abroad.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It is no surprise that his friend Giuseppe Baretti chose to make the *Dictionary* the model for his Italian—English dictionary of 1760, and for his Spanish dictionary nearly two decades later but there are numerous examples of influence beyond Johnson's own circle.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The *Dictionary* was exported to America.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] "The American adoption of the *Dictionary* was a momentous event not just in its history, but in the history of lexicography.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 1789 [Webster] declared that 'Great Britain, whose children we are, and whose language we speak, should no longer be *our* standard; for the taste of her writers is already corrupted, and her language on the decline.'" "Where Webster found fault with Johnson, Joseph Worcester saluted him ...
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 1846 he completed his *Universal and Critical Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Legislators are much occupied with ascertaining 'first meanings', with trying to secure the literal sense of their predecessors' legislation ...
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary came out in two forms.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The first was the 1755 *Folio* edition, which came in two large volumes on 4 April.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The folio edition also features full literary quotes by those authors that Johnson quoted, such as Dryden and Shakespeare.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It was followed a few weeks later by a second edition published in 165 weekly parts.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The third edition was published in 1765, but it was the fourth, which came out in 1773 which included significant revisions by Johnson of the original work.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The *Abridged* edition came out in 1756 in two octavo volumes with entries, "abstracted from the folio edition by the author", laid out as two columns per page.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The abridged version did not feature the literary quotes, just the author quoted.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This made it cheaper to produce and buy.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It sold over a thousand copies a year for the next 30 years bringing "The Dictionary" to the reach of every literate home.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's *Dictionary* has been available in replica editions for some years.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The entire first *Folio* editions of 1755 1st edition and 1773 4th edition are available on *Johnson's Dictionary Online*, a project funded by the National Endowment for the Humanities and created by a team of scholars at the University of Central Florida.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This version is the first fully searchable online edition.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The Preface to the *Dictionary* is available on Project Gutenberg.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In Melville's *Moby-Dick*, the narrator mentions using Johnson's dictionary to aid him in his leviathanic undertaking: "Fain am I to stagger to this emprise under the weightiest words of the dictionary.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] At the end of Chapter 1 of *Vanity Fair* by William Makepeace Thackeray, Becky Sharp disdainfully throws a copy of Johnson's *Dictionary* out the window.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's Great Dictionary" appears as a plot device in the 1944 Sherlock Holmes film *The Pearl of Death*, starring Basil Rathbone and Nigel Bruce.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson had given his only manuscript to the Prince of Wales and it was presumably destroyed by Blackadder's apprentice dogsbody Baldrick.
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The manuscript is later found intact, only for Johnson to discover he had forgotten to include the word "sausage".
[src:australian-english/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The episode ends with Baldrick throwing the dictionary into the fire.
[src:australian-english/a-new-english-dictionary] Unlike previous dictionaries, which had focused on documenting difficult words, *A New English Dictionary* was one of the first to focus on words in common usage.
[src:australian-english/a-new-english-dictionary] It was also the first to be written by a professional lexicographer.
[src:australian-english/a-new-english-dictionary] Kersey later continued his lexicographic career by enlarging Edward Phillips' *The New World of English Words* in 1706 and editing the *Dictionarium Anglo-Britannicum* in 1708.
[src:australian-english/a-new-english-dictionary] The original title of the *Oxford English Dictionary* was *A New English Dictionary on Historical Principles*, and it was sometimes given the abbreviation *NED*, for *New English Dictionary*.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is distinct from other accents in its county, such as the one spoken in Myddfai, due to separation by the Brecon Beacons, creating a substantial communication barrier between the two localities.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] It is more appropriate to associate it with neighbouring Swansea Valley, particularly the speech in northern areas (esp.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Ystalyfera and Ystradgynlais) since they are more similar to Abercraf than ones in its county.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] This could be seen from a survey where speakers could not discern the origins of the speech of Ystradgynlais and their hometown, but were able to discern Cwmtwrch with other villages in the valley.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf was entirely Welsh-speaking until World War II, when English-speaking evacuees settled in the village.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] It is a relatively young acquired dialect.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] This can be seen from generally less assimilation and elision and clear articulation unlike other accents in Powys or Swansea.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] As a more modern accent, it is restricted to the last two to three generations, with younger people being much more likely to speak it — though much of their daily life is conducted in Welsh, leading English to be taught as a second language.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is non-rhotic; /r/ is only pronounced before a vowel.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Like RP, linking and intrusive R is present in the system.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] On the other hand, the vowel system varies greatly from RP, unlike its consonants, which is stable in many English accents around the world.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] The offsets of the fronting diphthongs are near-close [ɪ], whereas the offsets of the backing diphthongs are close [u].
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf has kept some distinctions between diphthong–monophthong pronunciations; they are shared among other south Welsh dialects such as Port Talbot.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English generally follows West Glamorgan lexical incidence patterns.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] The vowel /ə/ is not elided, thus *factory*, *mandarin*, *reference* always have three syllables, unlike many accents such as RP or even Port Talbot.
[src:australian-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is considered to have a 'sing-song' or 'lilting' intonation due to having high amount of pitch on an unstressed post-tonic syllable, as well as pre-tonic syllables having a great degree of freedom, with a continuous rising pitch being common.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-english/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:australian-english/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English began to diverge from British and Hiberno-English after the First Fleet established the Colony of New South Wales in 1788.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English arose from a dialectal melting pot created by the intermingling of early settlers who were from a variety of dialectal regions of Great Britain and Ireland, though its most significant influences were the dialects of Southern England.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] By the 1820s, the native-born colonists' speech was recognisably distinct from speakers in Britain and Ireland.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English differs from other varieties in its phonology, pronunciation, lexicon, idiom, grammar and spelling.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English is relatively consistent across the continent, although it encompasses numerous regional and sociocultural varieties.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] "General Australian" describes the *de facto* standard dialect, which is perceived to be free of pronounced regional or sociocultural markers and is often used in the media.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Similar to early American English, Australian English passed through a process of extensive dialect levelling and mixing which produced a relatively homogeneous new variety of English which was easily understood by all.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The earliest Australian English was spoken by the first generation of native-born colonists in the Colony of New South Wales from the end of the 18th century.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] These native-born children were exposed to a wide range of dialects from across the British Isles.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The dialects of Southern England, including most notably the traditional Cockney dialect of London, were particularly influential on the development of the new variety and constituted "the major input of the various sounds that went into constructing" Australian English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] All the other regions of England were represented among the early colonists.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] A large proportion of early convicts and colonists were from Ireland (comprising 25% of the total convict population), and many of them spoke Irish as a sole or first language.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] They were joined by other non-native speakers of English from the Scottish Highlands and Wales.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Peter Miller Cunningham's 1827 book *Two Years in New South Wales* described the distinctive accent and vocabulary that had developed among the native-born colonists.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The first of the Australian gold rushes in the 1850s began a large wave of immigration, during which about two percent of the population of the United Kingdom emigrated to the colonies of New South Wales and Victoria.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The Gold Rushes brought immigrants and linguistic influences from many parts of the world.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] An example was the introduction of vocabulary from American English, including some terms later considered to be typically Australian, such as *bushwhacker* and *squatter*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The most obvious way in which Australian English is distinctive from other varieties of English is through its unique pronunciation.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] It shares most similarity with New Zealand English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Like most dialects of English, it is distinguished primarily by the phonetic quality of its vowels.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The vowels of Australian English can be divided according to length.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The long vowels, which include monophthongs and diphthongs, mostly correspond to the tense vowels used in analyses of Received Pronunciation (RP) as well as its centring diphthongs.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The short vowels, consisting only of monophthongs, correspond to the RP lax vowels.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] There exist pairs of long and short vowels with overlapping vowel quality giving Australian English phonemic length distinction, which is also present in some regional south-eastern dialects of the UK and eastern seaboard dialects in the US.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] An example of this feature is the distinction between *ferry* /ˈfeɹiː/ and *fairy* /ˈfeːɹiː/.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] As with New Zealand English and General American English, the weak-vowel merger is complete in Australian English: unstressed /ɪ/ is merged into /ə/ (schwa), unless it is followed by a velar consonant.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Examples of this feature are the following pairings, which are pronounced identically in Australian English: *Rosa's* and *roses*, as well as *Lennon* and *Lenin*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Other examples are the following pairs, which rhyme in Australian English: *abbott* with *rabbit*, and *dig it* with *bigot*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Most varieties of Australian English exhibit only a partial trap-bath split.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The words *bath*, *grass* and *can't* are always pronounced with the "long" /ɐː/ of *father*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Throughout the majority of the country, the "flat" /æ/ of *man* is the dominant pronunciation for the *a* vowel in the following words: *dance*, *advance*, *plant*, *example* and *answer*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The exception is the state of South Australia, where a more advanced trap-bath split is found, and where the dominant pronunciation of all the preceding words incorporates the "long" /ɐː/ of *father*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] There is little variation in the sets of consonants used in different English dialects but there are variations in how these consonants are used.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English is uniformly non-rhotic; that is, the /ɹ/ sound does not appear at the end of a syllable or immediately before a consonant.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] As with many non-rhotic dialects, linking /ɹ/ can occur when a word that has a final ⟨r⟩ in the spelling comes before another word that starts with a vowel.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] An intrusive /ɹ/ may similarly be inserted before a vowel in words that do not have ⟨r⟩ in the spelling in certain environments, namely after the long vowel /oː/ and after word final /ə/.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] This can be heard in "law-r-and order", where an intrusive R is voiced between the AW and the A.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] As with North American English, intervocalic alveolar flapping is a feature of Australian English: prevocalic /t/ and /d/ surface as the alveolar tap [ɾ] after sonorants other than /m, ŋ/ as well as at the end of a word or morpheme before any vowel in the same breath group.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Examples of this feature are that the following pairs are pronounced similarly or identically: *latter* and *ladder*, as well as *rated* and *raided*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In common with most varieties of Scottish English and American English, the phoneme /l/ is pronounced by Australians as a "dark" (velarised) *l* ([ɫ]) in almost all positions, unlike other dialects such as Received Pronunciation, Hiberno (Irish) English, etc.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Differences in stress, weak forms and standard pronunciation of isolated words occur between Australian English and other forms of English, which while noticeable do not impair intelligibility.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The affixes *-ary*, *-ery*, *-ory*, *-bury*, *-berry* and *-mony* (seen in words such as *necessary, mulberry* and *matrimony*) can be pronounced either with a full vowel (/ˈnesəseɹiː, ˈmalbeɹiː, ˈmætɹəməʉniː/) or a schwa (/ˈnesəsəɹiː, ˈmalbəɹiː, ˈmætɹəməniː/).
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Although some words like *necessary* are almost universally pronounced with the full vowel, older generations of Australians are relatively likely to pronounce these affixes with a schwa as is typical in British English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Meanwhile, younger generations are relatively likely to use a full vowel.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Words ending in unstressed *-ile* derived from Latin adjectives ending in *-ilis* are pronounced with a full vowel, so that *fertile* /ˈfɜːtɑel/ sounds like *fur tile* rather than rhyming with *turtle* /ˈtɜːtəl/.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In addition, miscellaneous pronunciation differences exist when compared with other varieties of English in relation to various isolated words, with some of those pronunciations being unique to Australian English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Relative to many other national dialect groupings, Australian English is relatively homogeneous across the country.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Some relatively minor regional differences in pronunciation exist.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] A limited range of word choices is strongly regional in nature.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Consequently, the geographical background of individuals may be inferred if they use words that are peculiar to particular Australian states or territories and, in some cases, even smaller regions.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In addition, some Australians speak creole languages derived from Australian English, such as Australian Kriol, Torres Strait Creole and Norfuk.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Academic research has also identified notable sociocultural variation within Australian English, which is mostly evident in phonology.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Although Australian English is relatively homogeneous, there are some regional variations.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The dialects of English spoken in the various states and territories of Australia differ slightly in vocabulary and phonology.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Most regional differences are in word usage.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Swimming clothes are known as *cossies*, /ˈkɔziːz/ *togs* or *swimmers* in New South Wales, *togs* in Queensland, and *bathers* in Victoria, Tasmania, Western Australia and South Australia.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] What Queensland calls a *stroller* is usually called a *pram* in Victoria, Western Australia, South Australia, New South Wales, and Tasmania.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Preference for some synonymous words also differ between states.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *Garbage* (i.e., garbage bin, garbage truck) dominates over *rubbish* in New South Wales and Queensland, while *rubbish* is more popular in Victoria, Tasmania, Western Australia and South Australia.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Additionally, the word *footy* generally refers to the most popular football code in an area; that is, rugby league or rugby union depending on the local area, in most of New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] More commonly *rugby* is used to distinguish rugby union from *footy* which refers to the more popular rugby league.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *Footy* commonly is used for Australian rules football elsewhere however the term refers to the both prominent codes, rugby league and Australian rules football, interchangeably, depending on context of usage outside of regional perrameters.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In some pockets of Melbourne & Western Sydney *football* and more rarely *footy* will refer to association football although unlike more common international terminology, Australian English uses the term *soccer* and not *football* or *footy*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Beer glasses are also named differently in different states.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Distinctive grammatical patterns exist such as the use of the interrogative *eh* (also spelled *ay* or *aye*), which is particularly associated with Queensland.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *Secret Santa* () and *Kris Kringle* are used in all states, with the former being more common in Queensland.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The most pronounced variation in phonology is between South Australia and the other states and territories.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The trap–bath split is more complete in South Australia, in contrast to the other states.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Accordingly, words such as *dance*, *advance*, *plant*, *example* and *answer* are pronounced with /ɐː/ (as in *father*) far more frequently in South Australia while the older /æ/ (as in *mad*) is dominant elsewhere in Australia.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *L*-vocalisation is also more common in South Australia than other states.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In Western Australian and Queensland English, the vowels in *near* and *square* are typically realised as centring diphthongs ([nɪə, skweə]), whereas in the other states they may also be realised as monophthongs: [nɪː, skweː].
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] A feature common in Victorian English is salary–celery merger, whereby a Victorian pronunciation of *Ellen* may sound like *Alan* and Victoria's capital city *Melbourne* may sound like *Malbourne* to speakers from other states.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] There is also regional variation in /ʉː/ before /l/ (as in *school* and *pool*).
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In some parts of Australia, notably Victoria, a fully backed allophone of /ʉː/, transcribed [ʊː], is common before /l/.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] As a result, the pairs full/fool and pull/pool differ phonetically only in vowel length for those speakers.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The usual allophone for /ʉː/ is further forward in Queensland and New South Wales than Victoria.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] A *final particle but*, where "but" is the concluding word in a sentence, has also evolved as a distinctive feature in Australian English, particularly in Western Australia and Queensland.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In conversational Australian English it is thought to be a turn-yielding particle that marks contrastive content in the utterance it closes.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] It is a linguistic trait sometimes employed in Australian literature to indicate that the character is quintessentially Australian.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The General Australian accent serves as the standard variety of English across the country.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] According to linguists, it emerged during the 19th century.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] General Australian is the dominant variety across the continent, and is particularly so in urban areas.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The increasing dominance of General Australian reflects its prominence on radio and television since the latter half of the 20th century.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Recent generations have seen a comparatively smaller proportion of the population speaking with the *Broad* sociocultural variant, which differs from General Australian in its phonology.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The Broad variant is found across the continent and is relatively more prominent in rural and outer-suburban areas.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] A largely historical *Cultivated* sociocultural variant, which adopted features of British Received Pronunciation and which was commonplace in official media during the early 20th century, had become largely extinct by the onset of the 21st century.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian Aboriginal English is made up of a range of forms which developed differently in different parts of Australia, and are said to vary along a continuum, from forms close to Standard Australian English to more non-standard forms.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] There are distinctive features of accent, grammar, words and meanings, as well as language use.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Academics have noted the emergence of numerous ethnocultural dialects of Australian English that are spoken by people from some minority non-English speaking backgrounds.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] These ethnocultural varieties contain features of General Australian English as adopted by the children of immigrants blended with some non-English language features, such as Afro-Asiatic languages and languages of Asia.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Samoan English is also influencing Australian English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Other ethnolects include those of Lebanese and Vietnamese Australians.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] A high rising terminal in Australian English was noted and studied earlier than in other varieties of English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The feature is sometimes called *Australian questioning intonation*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Research published in 1986, regarding vernacular speech in Sydney, suggested that high rising terminal was initially spread by young people in the 1960s.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] It found that the high rising terminal was used more than twice as often by young people than older people, and is more common among women than men.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In the United Kingdom, it has occasionally been considered one of the variety's stereotypical features, and its spread there is attributed to the popularity of Australian soap operas.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English has many words and idioms which are unique to the dialect.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Internationally well-known examples of Australian terminology include *outback*, meaning a remote, sparsely populated area, *the bush*, meaning either a native forest or a country area in general, and *g'day*, a greeting.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *Dinkum*, or *fair dinkum* means "true", "legitimate" or "is that true?", among other things, depending on context and inflection.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The derivative *dinky-di* means "true" or devoted: a "dinky-di Aussie" is a "true Australian".
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian poetry, such as "The Man from Snowy River", as well as folk songs such as "Waltzing Matilda", contain many historical Australian words and phrases that are understood by Australians even though some are not in common usage today.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English, in common with British English, uses the word *mate* to mean *friend*, as well as the word *bloody* as a mild expletive or intensifier.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] "Mate" is also used in multiple ways including to indicate "mateship" or formally call out the target of a threat or insult, depending on intonation and context.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Several words used by Australians were at one time used in the UK but have since fallen out of usage or changed in meaning there.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Some elements of Aboriginal languages have been adopted by Australian English—mainly as names for places, flora and fauna (for example dingo) and local culture.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Many such are localised, and do not form part of general Australian use, while others, such as *kangaroo*, *boomerang*, *budgerigar*, *wallaby* and so on have become international.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Other examples are *cooee* and *hard yakka*.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The former is used as a high-pitched call, for attracting attention, (pronounced /ˈkʉːiː/) which travels long distances.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *Cooee* is also a notional distance: "if he's within *cooee*, we'll spot him".
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] *Hard yakka* means "hard work" and is derived from *yakka*, from the Jagera/Yagara language once spoken in the Brisbane region.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The word *bung*, meaning "dead" was originally a Yagara word which was used in the pidgin widely spoken across Australia.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Many towns or suburbs of Australia have also been influenced or named after Aboriginal words.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The best-known example is the capital, Canberra, named after a local Ngunnawal language word thought to mean "women's breasts" or "meeting place".
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Litotes, such as "not bad", "not much" and "you're not wrong", are also used.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Diminutives and hypocorisms are common and are often used to indicate familiarity.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Some common examples are *arvo* (afternoon), *barbie* (barbecue), *smoko* (cigarette break), *Aussie* (Australian) and *Straya* (Australia).
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] This may also be done with people's names to create nicknames (other English speaking countries create similar diminutives).
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] For example, "Gazza" from Gary, or "Smitty" from John Smith.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The use of the suffix *-o* originates in Irish: *ó*, which is both a postclitic and a suffix with much the same meaning as in Australian English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] In informal speech, incomplete comparisons are sometimes used, such as "sweet as" (as in "That car is sweet as.").
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] "Full", "fully" or "heaps" may precede a word to act as an intensifier (as in "The waves at the beach were heaps good.").
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] This was more common in regional Australia and South Australia but has been in common usage in urban Australia for decades.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] The suffix "-ly" is sometimes omitted in broader Australian English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] For instance, "really good" can become "real good".
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australia's switch to the metric system in the 1970s changed most of the country's vocabulary of measurement from imperial to metric measures.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Since the switch to metric, heights of people are listed in centimetres on official documents and distances by road on signs are listed in terms of kilometres and metres.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] There are extensive terms used in other varieties of English which are not widely used in Australian English.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] These terms usually do not result in Australian English speakers failing to comprehend speakers of other varieties of English, as Australian English speakers will often be familiar with such terms through exposure to media or may ascertain the meaning using context.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English has influenced several other varieties of English, particularly in Oceania, and other languages spoken in Australia and Oceania.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] Australian English has been a heavy source of vocabulary for both English and French (plus in turn local languages) in New Caledonia, with a large amount of Australianised Anglicisms being present in New Caledonian speech.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p01] For example, the Australian agricultural terms *paddock*, *run*, *station*, *stock*, *stockman*, *stockwhip* and *stockyard* are all used in New Caledonia.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The general rules which apply to Australian English are described at English grammar.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Grammatical differences between varieties of English are minor relative to differences in phonology and vocabulary and do not generally affect intelligibility.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] As in all English-speaking countries, there is no central authority that prescribes official usage with respect to matters of spelling, grammar, punctuation or style.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] There are several dictionaries of Australian English which adopt a descriptive approach.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The *Macquarie Dictionary* and the *Australian Oxford Dictionary* are most commonly used by universities, governments and courts as the standard for Australian English spelling.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Australian spelling is significantly closer to British compared with American spelling, as it did not adopt the systematic reforms promulgated in Noah Webster's 1828 Dictionary.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Notwithstanding, the Macquarie Dictionary often lists most American spellings as acceptable secondary variants.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Unspaced forms such as *onto*, *anytime*, *alright* and *anymore* are also listed as being equally as acceptable as their spaced counterparts.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Additionally, the spellings *donut* and *percent* as opposed to *doughnut* and *per cent* have become more common than their counterparts; however, the official Australian style manual considers *percent* to be a misspelling.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] There is variation between and within varieties of English in the treatment of **-t** and **-ed** endings for past tense verbs.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The Macquarie Dictionary does not favour either, but it suggests that *leap**ed***, *lean**ed*** or *learn**ed*** (with **-ed** endings) are more common but *spel**t*** and *burn**t*** (with **-t** endings) are more common.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Different spellings have existed throughout Australia's history.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] What are today regarded as American spellings were popular in Australia throughout the late 19th and early 20th centuries, with the Victorian Department of Education endorsing them into the 1970s and *The Age* newspaper until the 1990s.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] This influence can be seen in the spelling of the Australian Labor Party and also in some place names such as Victor Harbor.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The *Concise Oxford English Dictionary* has been credited with re-establishing the dominance of the British spellings in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] For a short time during the late 20th century, Harry Lindgren's 1969 spelling reform proposal (Spelling Reform 1 or SR1) gained some support in Australia and was adopted by the Australian Teachers' Federation and minister Doug Everingham in personal correspondence.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] A prominent style guide for the Government of Australia is the *Australian Government Style Manual.* It is a comprehensive guide that includes usage guides on grammar, punctuation, and conventions for government writers and editors.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] To indicate speech, both single and double inverted comma quotation marks are used.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Generally, double quotation marks are preferred for use in the first instance, with single quotation marks used for quotes within quotes.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] However, the opposite is true in the government and corporate sectors, where double quotation marks are reserved for quotes within quotes.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The punctuation mark used to end a sentence is called a full stop; a period usually refers to menstruation or an interval of time.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The DD/MM/YYYY date format is followed and the 12-hour clock is generally used in everyday life (the 24-hour clock is used by the military and police, and for transport timetables).
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] The country has used the metric system since the 1970s, though the imperial system is still sometimes used informally, especially among older Australians, in idioms (e.g. to "go the extra mile", not "go the extra kilometre") and in reference to a person's height.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] In betting, decimal odds are used in preference to fractional odds, as used in the United Kingdom, or moneyline odds in the United States.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] There are two major English language keyboard layouts, the United States layout and the United Kingdom layout.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Keyboards and keyboard software for the Australian market universally uses the US keyboard layout, which lacks the pound (£), euro and negation symbols and uses a different layout for punctuation symbols from the UK keyboard layout.
[src:australian-english/australian-english-p02] Percentage of people who speak another language at home who are fluent in English.
